{\sffamily\Large\bfseries\textcolor{pcbDark}{Abstract}}
\end{center}
\vspace{4pt}
\noindent
This report documents the complete engineering workflow behind a \textbf{standalone digital clock} built around the bare \textbf{ATmega328P-PU} microcontroller -- the same chip that powers the Arduino Uno, used here without the Arduino board itself. The project follows a deliberate, industry-style path: requirement-driven \textbf{component selection}, supporting \textbf{engineering calculations} (crystal load capacitance, segment current-limiting resistors, decoupling and reset networks), a \textbf{breadboard prototype on an Arduino Uno} to validate display multiplexing and button logic, migration to the \textbf{bare ATmega328P-PU chip}, \textbf{bootloader burning} using a second Arduino Uno configured as an AVR ISP programmer, \textbf{firmware upload}, full-circuit \textbf{breadboard re-validation}, permanent \textbf{soldering}, and finally a custom \textbf{snap-fit enclosure} modelled in Autodesk Fusion 360 and 3D printed after slicing in Creality's slicer software. Every design decision -- from the 22\,pF crystal capacitors to the 330\,$\Omega$ segment resistors -- is backed by a calculation, making this document a complete reference for anyone wishing to reproduce, audit, or extend the build.

