\section{Introduction}
% =========================================================

\subsection{Motivation}
Most beginner digital-clock projects stop at "upload code to an Arduino board and watch the display blink." That is a fine starting point, but it stops short of the question every embedded engineer eventually has to answer: \emph{what happens once you remove the development board?} An Arduino Uno is, underneath the USB connector, the voltage regulator, and the FTDI/CH340 chip, simply a breakout board for one microcontroller -- the \textbf{ATmega328P}. This project was undertaken to deliberately strip away that convenience layer and rebuild the same functionality around the bare chip, going through every step a product team would: selecting parts for a reason, calculating support-component values instead of guessing them, validating logic on a breadboard, porting the firmware to the standalone microcontroller, burning a bootloader, soldering a permanent board, and finally packaging the result in a custom-designed, 3D-printed enclosure.

\subsection{Project Objective}
\begin{infobox}[Objective]
To design and implement a \textbf{standalone digital clock} using an \textbf{ATmega328P-PU} microcontroller (rather than a complete Arduino board), demonstrating the full embedded-product development pipeline -- from idea to a finished, enclosed device -- and to document every design choice with the calculation that justifies it.
\end{infobox}

The final device displays the time on four multiplexed seven-segment displays and accepts user input through three push buttons, with two operating modes (\textit{Normal} and \textit{Seconds}) described in Section~\ref{sec:features}.

\subsection{Development Workflow at a Glance}
The project was executed as eight sequential phases, each building on the validation done in the one before it. This mirrors how a real embedded product moves from concept to manufacture: nothing is soldered until it has been proven on a breadboard, and nothing is enclosed until the soldered board itself is verified.

