\begin{designnote}[Why this order matters]
Logic is validated on the \textbf{Arduino Uno} first because its USB bootloader and on-board regulator make iteration fast -- mistakes there cost a re-upload, not a re-solder. Only after the segment mapping, multiplexing, and button logic are confirmed correct does the design move to the bare chip, where mistakes are costlier to fix.
\end{designnote}

% =========================================================
\section{Final Feature Set}
\label{sec:features}
% =========================================================
The firmware implements two display modes and a simple three-button control scheme, chosen to keep the user interface minimal while still allowing full time-setting capability.

\subsection{Normal Mode --- HH:MM}
This is the default, always-returned-to display mode. The four digits show hours and minutes, separated by a colon built from two LEDs, e.g.:
\begin{center}
{\Huge\sffamily\bfseries\textcolor{pcbDark}{14:35}}
\end{center}

\subsection{Seconds Mode --- MM:SS}
A long press of the \textit{Start/Mode} button switches the display to minutes and seconds:
\begin{center}
{\Huge\sffamily\bfseries\textcolor{copper}{35:27}}
\end{center}
After a short timeout, the firmware automatically reverts to Normal Mode, so the clock never gets "stuck" showing seconds.

\subsection{User Controls}
Three momentary push buttons, wired with internal pull-ups, provide the entire user interface:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\rowcolor{pcbDark}
\textcolor{white}{\textbf{Button}} & \textcolor{white}{\textbf{Label}} & \textcolor{white}{\textbf{Function}} \\
\midrule
Button 1 & \textsc{Hour}  & Increment the hour value \\
Button 2 & \textsc{Minute} & Increment the minute value \\
Button 3 & \textsc{Start/Mode} & Start the clock from a set time / toggle Seconds Mode \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\begin{designnote}[Active-Low Button Logic]
With the internal pull-up resistors enabled in firmware, each button pin idles \textbf{HIGH}. Pressing a button pulls the pin to \textbf{LOW} (ground). The firmware therefore treats a logic-0 read as "pressed" -- no external pull-up/pull-down resistors are required on the board.
\end{designnote}

