\subsection{Bootloader Burning Procedure}
\begin{enumerate}
\item Open the Arduino IDE, load the built-in \textbf{File\,$\to$\,Examples\,$\to$\,11.ArduinoISP\,$\to$\,ArduinoISP} sketch, and upload it to the \emph{programmer} Uno (with its own USB cable connected, board still selected as ``Arduino Uno'').
\item Wire the programmer Uno to the target ATmega328P-PU on the breadboard exactly as in Table~\ref{tab:isp} / Figure~\ref{fig:ispwiring}. The target chip must already have its minimum operating circuit (Section~\ref{sec:phase2}) in place.
\item In the IDE, set \textbf{Tools\,$\to$\,Board\,$\to$\,Arduino Uno} (this selects the correct bootloader image and fuse settings for the target chip) and \textbf{Tools\,$\to$\,Programmer\,$\to$\,Arduino as ISP}.
\item Run \textbf{Tools\,$\to$\,Burn Bootloader}. The IDE uses the programmer Uno to write the bootloader and set the fuses (clock source = external crystal, brown-out detection, etc.) on the target chip.
\item Confirm a "Done burning bootloader" message with no errors before proceeding.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{warnbox}[Common Pitfall]
If the target chip's crystal and capacitors (Section~\ref{sec:crystalcalc}) are not yet wired up at this point, bootloader burning will fail or hang -- the ISP process depends on the target chip actually running at the expected clock speed once fuses referencing an external crystal are set.
\end{warnbox}

