\section{Phase VI --- Soldering \& Permanent Assembly}
\label{sec:phase6}
% =========================================================

\subsection{From Breadboard to Solder}
Once Table~\ref{tab:fullvalidation} was fully green, the validated layout was transferred, connection for connection, onto a perforated dot board for permanent assembly.

\subsection{Soldering Precautions}
\begin{itemize}
\item Keep crystal leads and the two 22\,pF capacitor leads as \textbf{short as possible} -- long leads here add stray inductance/capacitance that can destabilise oscillation.
\item Double-check \textbf{polarity} on every polarised part (LEDs, electrolytic capacitors if used) before soldering -- a reversed LED simply won't light, but a reversed electrolytic can fail violently.
\item Verify the \textbf{chip orientation} (notch / pin-1 dot, Figure~\ref{fig:pinout}) before inserting it into a socket -- never solder the chip directly without a socket, both to protect it from soldering heat and to allow future reprogramming or replacement.
\item Inspect every joint for \textbf{solder bridges} between adjacent pins, especially across the closely-spaced DIP-28 socket pins.
\item Use a fine-tip iron and \textbf{check continuity} with a multimeter on every power and ground run before first power-up.
\item Power up for the first time \textbf{without} the microcontroller inserted, verify 5\,V and 0\,V land where expected, then insert the chip.
\end{itemize}

