\section{Phase VII --- Mechanical Enclosure Design (Fusion 360)}
\label{sec:phase7}
% =========================================================

\subsection{Design Goals}
With a working soldered board in hand, a custom enclosure was modelled in \textbf{Autodesk Fusion 360} to:
\begin{itemize}
\item Physically protect the board, solder joints, and wiring;
\item Present a clean, finished, non-prototype appearance;
\item Provide a display window so the seven-segment digits remain clearly visible;
\item Provide access cut-outs aligned to the three push buttons;
\item Assemble and disassemble \textbf{without screws}, using a snap-fit joint between the two shells.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Snap-Fit Mechanism}
\label{sec:snapfit}
Rather than threaded fasteners, the enclosure's top and bottom shells lock together using a series of cantilever snap hooks moulded into the bottom shell, which engage matching lips/slots printed into the inside wall of the top shell (Figure~\ref{fig:snapfit}).

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0, line width=1pt]
% top shell wall (cross-section)
\draw[draw=pcbDark, fill=pcbMint] (0,2) rectangle (1.0,3.2);
\draw[draw=pcbDark, fill=pcbMint] (0,1.6) -- (0,2) -- (-0.55,2) -- (-0.55,1.75) -- (0,1.6);
\node[font=\sffamily\footnotesize, anchor=south] at (0.5,3.25) {Top shell wall};
\node[font=\sffamily\footnotesize, color=copper, anchor=east] at (-0.65,2.15) {Lip};

% bottom shell wall + cantilever hook
\draw[draw=pcbDark, fill=pcbDark2] (0,0) rectangle (1.0,1.55);
\draw[draw=pcbDark, fill=pcbDark2] (0,1.55) -- (0,1.95) -- (-0.55,1.7) -- cycle;
\node[font=\sffamily\footnotesize, anchor=north] at (0.5,-0.05) {Bottom shell wall};
\node[font=\sffamily\footnotesize, color=circuitGold, anchor=east] at (-0.65,1.45) {Snap hook};

\draw[-{Stealth[length=2mm]}, color=copper, line width=0.8pt] (2.0,2.6) -- (1.1,2.05);
\node[font=\sffamily\footnotesize, align=left] at (3.3,2.6) {Hook flexes past\\the lip, then springs\\back to lock};
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Snap-fit joint cross-section: a cantilever hook on the bottom shell deflects past, then springs back behind, a matching lip on the top shell.}
\label{fig:snapfit}
\end{figure}

\begin{designnote}[Why snap-fit over screws]
A screwed enclosure needs bosses, threaded inserts or self-tapping pilot holes, and visible fastener heads. A snap-fit shell needs none of that: it assembles with a firm press, disassembles by releasing the hooks with a thin tool, and leaves a cleaner, hardware-free exterior -- at the cost of needing slightly more careful tolerancing (typically 0.2--0.3\,mm clearance between hook and lip) so the joint is snug without being so tight that the PLA hook snaps off during assembly.
\end{designnote}

