\section{Results \& Final Outcome}
\label{sec:results}
% =========================================================
The completed device is a fully standalone, enclosed digital clock built around a bare ATmega328P-PU rather than an Arduino board. It reliably displays HH:MM in Normal Mode, switches to MM:SS in Seconds Mode on demand, accepts hour/minute/start-mode input from three buttons, and runs continuously from a simple 5\,V USB supply -- all inside a custom, snap-fit, 3D-printed shell with no exposed fasteners.

\begin{infobox}[Outcome Summary]
\textbf{Idea} $\to$ \textbf{Calculated component selection} $\to$ \textbf{Arduino Uno breadboard prototype} $\to$ \textbf{Standalone ATmega328P-PU} $\to$ \textbf{ISP bootloader \& firmware burning} $\to$ \textbf{Full-circuit re-validation} $\to$ \textbf{Soldered assembly} $\to$ \textbf{Fusion 360 snap-fit enclosure} $\to$ \textbf{3D-printed final product}.
\end{infobox}

